96. eeu pulvere .. .] ‘ as when the scorched wayfarer comes from deep dust (i.e. a road deep in dust) and spits the dirt from his parched mouth ⁷. Columella (9. 10) quoting this passage, writes deterior sordido sputo (‘ spittle ³) similis, tam foedus quam puluere ἰ’ἱαῐον, and so makes Virgil compare the bee to the actual spittle of a dusty traveller. Such a coarse comparison seems however precluded‚ not merely as a matter of taste, but because it is the condition of the traveller himself which is the main subject of the sentence, the fact of his spitting being introduced incidentally to illustrate that condition. Moreover, throughout, the bees are compared to men and not to things, while the words turpes horrens, which Virgil applies to these bees, are far inore applicable to nien who have been plodding through dust and dirt than to spittle.
